</head><body lang=3D"EN"><h2>The Jacobian for Polar and Spherical Coordinat=
es
</h2><p>
We first compute the Jacobian for the change of variables
from Cartesian coordinates to <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.=
edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/coord/coord=
.html">polar
coordinates</a>.
</p><p>
Recall that
</p><p>
<img width=3D"409" height=3D"17" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath50" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img1.gif">
</p><p>
Hence,
</p><p>
<img width=3D"449" height=3D"17" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath52" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img2.gif">
</p><p>
The <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/und=
ergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/change/change.html#jacobian">Jacobian=
</a> is
</p><p>
<img width=3D"418" height=3D"18" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath54" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img3.gif">
</p><p>
</p><hr>
<b>Correction</b>
There is a typo in this last formula for J. The (-r*cos(theta)) term
should be (r*cos(theta)).=20
<hr>
<p>
Here we use the identity cos^2(theta)+sin^2(theta)=3D1.
</p><p>
The above result is <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/h=
ome/programs/undergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/255pol/255pol.html">a=
nother way of deriving
the result</a> dA=3Drdrd(theta).
</p><p>
Now we compute compute the Jacobian for the change of variables
from Cartesian coordinates to <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.=
edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/coord/coord=
.html">spherical
coordinates</a>.
</p><p>
Recall that
</p><p>
<img width=3D"425" height=3D"17" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath56" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img4.gif">
</p><p>
</p><p>
The <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/und=
ergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/change/change.html#jacobian">Jacobian=
</a> is given by:
</p><p>
<img width=3D"406" height=3D"68" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath58" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img5.gif">
</p><p>
Plugging in the various derivatives, we get
</p><p>
<img width=3D"514" height=3D"68" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath60" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img6.gif">
</p><p>
</p><hr>
<b>Correction</b>
The entry -rho*cos(phi) in the bottom row of the above matrix
SHOULD BE -rho*sin(phi).
<hr>

Computing this <a href=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/p=
rograms/undergrad/CalculusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/deter/deter.html">determin=
ant</a>, we get
<p>
<img width=3D"294" height=3D"21" align=3D"BOTTOM" alt=3D"displaymath62" src=
=3D"https://sites.science.oregonstate.edu/math/home/programs/undergrad/Calc=
ulusQuestStudyGuides/vcalc/jacpol/img7.gif">
</p><p></p><hr>
